Since the major aim of our present study is to detect the citrate using water soluble, biocompatible TAG-CDs, the preliminary performance was evaluated using spectrophotometric titrations, the obtained UV–vis spectra was shown in Fig. 3
                        A. The TAG-CDs shows an absorption band at 294 nm Curve a, while titrated with 0.1 µM of citrate the absorption peak intensity increased concurrently with red shift (Curve b). Further raising the concentration of citrate in each 0.1 µM addition to the probe solution, not only enhancing the absorption intensity linearly but also red-shifted from 294 to 303 nm as shown in Curves c-k. The observed red shift in the absorbance spectra Fig. 3A is assumed that the increased size of TAG-CDs after interacting with citrate (Scheme 2
                        ). The sensitive detection of citrate using TAG-CDs were achieved by spectrofluorimetric titrations. The probe TAG-CDs at optimum conditions show an emission peak at 396 nm with its corresponding excitation at 303 nm, stoke’s shift was observed to be 93 nm (Fig. 3B, curve a). After the introduction of 50 nM citrate to the TAG-CDs, fluorescence intensity was quenched without changing its emission wavelength (curve b). Further increasing the concentration of citrate by each 50 nM up to 650 nM, the emission intensity was dropped down linearly at 396 nm. The obtained plot between the fluorescence intensity versus the concentration of citrate was displayed in the inset of Fig. 3B. It seems that, the observed fluorescence trend shows good linearity against citrate concentration with the correlation coefficient of 0.9854, based on the obtained slope value the LOD was found to be 4 nM. The lowest LOD value was obtained by the present probe is worth when compared with earlier reports in citrate sensor using small organic receptors and carbon dots (Table 1
                        ).
